### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

_No response_

### Description

In Reactive Forms, we can disable/enable the entire form tree imperatively via:

```typescript
form.disable();
form.enable();
```

With Signal Forms, there is still a `disabled()` state on fields (and the root form aggregates field state), but there is currently no supported equivalent to disable/enable the entire form tree.

If I create a Signal Form like this:

```typescript
export const conferenceInitialState = {
  name: '',
  startDate: new Date(),
  endDate: new Date(),
  online: false,
  url: '',
  location: '',
  description: '',
};

readonly conferenceModel = signal(conferenceInitialState);
readonly conferenceForm = form(this.conferenceModel);
```

I can read form state signals such as:

```
this.conferenceForm().disabled();
```

‚Ä¶but `conferenceForm().disabled()` is never true because no mechanism exists to apply a form-level disabled rule (only field-level rules via schema).

To disable multiple fields today, I need to define a top-level signal and apply disabled(...) per field:
```
readonly formDisabled = signal(false);

readonly conferenceForm = form(this.conferenceModel, (path) => {
  disabled(path.name, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.startDate, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.endDate, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.online, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.url, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.location, () => this.formDisabled());
  disabled(path.description, () => this.formDisabled());
});
```

This is correct, but becomes very repetitive for larger forms (especially with nesting).
I tried to reduce repetition with a helper:

```typescript
function disableAll<T>(
  fields: SchemaPathTree<T>,
  isDisabled: () => boolean
) {
  Object.values(fields).forEach(field => {
    disabled(field as any, isDisabled);
  });
}
```

Usage:

```typescript
readonly conferenceForm = form(this.conferenceModel, (path) => {
  disableAll(path, () => this.formDisabled());
});
```

The disabled state never reacts to Signal changes.


### Proposed solution

It would be very helpful to have a first-class way to disable or enable the entire form tree, similar to Reactive Forms. So either.

```typescript
conferenceForm.disable();
conferenceForm.enable();
```

or some disableAll built in helper:

```typescript
disableAll(schema, isFormDisabled)
```

